defaultLocal Government and the Prudential Framework
default4.5
default              
defaultB
defaultorrowing and capital expenditure in local 
defaultgovernment is
default controlled by the prudential framework.
default  
defaultTh
defaultis
default encompasses primary legislation
default, u
defaultnderlying regulation in the form of a statutory instrument, a professional code of practice – CIPFA’s Prudential Code for Capital 
defaultF
defaultinance in Local Authorities
default and the requirement for elected members to approve capital expenditure plans and associated borr
defaultowing and investment decisions.  
default4.
default6
default              
defaultThe objectives of the Prudential Code are
default to ensure
default that:
default4.7
default              
defaultThe
default code is supported by a suite of prescribed prudential indicators which are designed to allow the council to test the affordability and sustainability of the proposed debt
default and to be assured that treasury management decisions are in accordance with good practice.  
defaultThe prudential indicators are in the public domain
default and 
defaultrequire to be approved by elected members as part of the plans for capital expenditure.
default4.8
default              
defaultIn submitting 
defaultevidence to the Commission on Scottish Devolution
default and to the Scottish Parliament’s Scotland Bill Committee
default we recommended that a robust control mechanism was necessary to ensure effective Parliamentary scrutiny.
default  
default4.9
default              
default In its report on borrowing powers a
defaultnd innovative approaches to capital funding, the Assembly’s Finance Committee adopted the principles of the Prudential Code in their recommendation that:
defaultIf the Welsh Government were granted
default 
defaultborrowing powers, proposals for upper limits for its borrowing
default 
defaultrequirements, demonstrating affordability, sustainability and
default 
defaultprudence, should be presented to the Assembly within the budget
default 
defaultmotion.
default4.1
default0
default              
defaultThis recommendation was accepted in principle by the Welsh Government:
defaultThe Welsh Government accepts that borrowing s
defaulthould be affordable, sustainable and prudent, and that the Assembly should be able to exercise its oversight and scrutiny roles in relation to borrowing as it does with other financial activities of the Welsh Government through the budget process and other
default mechanisms
default.
default4
default.
default1
default1
default              
defaultHowever, the draft Bill appears to contain no provision requiring that the Assembly have oversight of the Welsh Government’s borrowing powers by requiring approval or authorisation of their plans to borrow.
default  Again, there is a requirement to report to the Assembly 
defaultex ante
default, however this does not allow the Assembly the appropriate consideration of the Welsh Government’s borrowing plans and whether these are affordable and sustainable in the long term.
default4.12
default              
defaultThe 
defaultabsence of a control framework
default from the draft Bill
default is an omission which requires further 
defaultconsideration
default.  Without a prescribed control framework, scrutiny and control of borrowing and capital expenditure by the Assembly will be less effective.   
default&#xa0;
defaultAffordabi
defaultlity of borrowing
default4.1
default3
default              
defaultThe fundamental objective of affordability is to ensure that capital investment remains within sustainable limits and to consider the impact upon the budget and on local tax.  
default4.14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe ability of local government to fund the revenue cons
defaultequences arising from lending comes principally from grant paid by the Welsh Government and from the power to raise local taxation in the form of council tax. 
default4.15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe consequences of capital expenditure funded by borrowing are the repayment of the borrowing itself and the repayment 
defaultof 
defaultinterest.  
defaultLocal g
defaultovernment statute dictates that liabilities from external borrowing have ‘first call’ on revenues, before any other
default type of expenditure.
default 
default4.16
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe decision to undertake capital expenditure and subsequently pay interest and to repay external debt will represent a significant opportunity cost for the 
defaultWelsh
default Government.  Clearly, this will com
defaulte at the expense of
default revenue expendi
defaultture
default on services
default.  Unlike the clarity with 
defaultthe local
default government legislation, the draft Bill is not clear which income source the borrowing by the Welsh Government will be secured upon.
default&#xa0;
defaultNeed for 
defaultcapital 
defaultinvestment
default4.17
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBorrowing is intended to fund capital 
defaultinve
defaultstment
default and it is therefore essential that the need for borrowing is underpinned by a clear asset management strategy.  
defaultSimplistically, asset management planning considers future service delivery need.  That need then influences 
defaultinvestment decisions which 
defaultdrive
default the need for borrowing.  This can be contrasted with the practice under the previous control framework where the financial cap, rather than service need, dictated investment.
default4.18
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Prudential Code prescribes that, in making its capital investment decis
defaultions, the authority must have explicit regard to option appraisal, asset management planning, strategic planning for the authority and achievability of the forward plan.  
default4.19
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default              
defaultThe 
defaultprescription that investment decisions (and therefore borrowing decisions) must
default have explicit regard to asset management is not evident in the 
defaultdraft 
defaultBill. 
default&#xa0;
defaultComparison with the 
defaultScotland Act 2012
default4
default.
default20
default              
defaultThe 
defaultScotland Act 2012
default gives the Scottish Ministers the power to borrow for capital investment, limited to 10% of the Scottish Governmen
defaultt’s capital DEL each year within a statutory total of £2.2 billion.
default  There appears to be no similar annual profile of borrowing set out for Wales in the draft Bill.
default4.
default21
default              
defaultIf the Welsh Government were given powers on the same basis as Scotland, i.e. 10% of 
defaultthe capital DEL in each year, then the limit on borrowing for the 2014-15 
defaultfinancial year would be around £142 million.
default  Such an annual profile on borrowing could prevent the situation where the entire borrowing limit is utilised at an early stage.
default4.
default2
default2
default              
defaultTh
defaulte 
defaultScotland Act 2012
default also sets out that loans for capital purposes will generally be for a maximum of 10 years, with the option of this being extended in line with the life of the asset in question.  The draft Bill appears to state no time limits on the lif
defaulte of the debt of the Welsh Government, thus providing no safeguard for debt extending far into the future and potentially creating a burden on future generations.
